text: Billy woods hi everyone
Anthony Fantino here the Internet's
busiest music nerd and it's time for a
review of the new Billy woods album
Billy woods is a mysterious DC based
rapper who kind of jump-started his
long-running solo career with an
incredibly dark topical lyrical and
moody hip-hop album last year history
will absolve me and as far as woods rap
style goes he has this flow that sort of
blurs lines between rapping and spoken
word sort of ranting and the way Billy
delivers these lyrics comes off really
forceful convincing the meaning of what
Billy is saying for the most part hits
at least me very instantaneously because
he tries his best to be a very vivid
storyteller a communicator and emotion
conveyor and the guy makes some really
great production choices as well which
brings me to why door candy is sort of a
unique moment for Billy in his career
he's got all the production handled by
one single person a pretty popular
underground hip hop producer blockhead
who of course is most famous for his
work with Aesop Rock when I first heard
of Billy working with a producer for the
length of an entire album on this new
project I was pretty excited about the
concept potential behind door candy and
I gotta say after numerous listens to
this album there is a significant theme
at least if not a story running through
this album and it's a theme that really
delivers on the title here you have the
word door which isn't an often used word
but means things like gloomy severe and
candy which i think is sort of a piece
of symbolism for drugs which are often
mentioned throughout this LP and not
just really doing them or getting
addicted to them having them ruin your
life mostly selling them it's really a
story of someone who was living really
small time while selling drugs and just
kind of the life that this person is
leading and and this story may be more
personal than Billy lets on and on top
of this blockhead lends some really good
production to this
LP not incredibly layered or flashy or
anything like that there are a few
moments that get really melodic and and
sort of progressive like his old Aesop
Rock production but for the most part
the instrumentals on the cell P feel
eerie they feel rough they set the stage
for something that feels like some
crimes are going to be committed some
harsh realities are going to be exposed
it's one grimy sample after another in
kick drums and snares that don't so much
boom or bang but really just sort of
thud still the roughness of these beats
doesn't stop blockhead from getting
really creative with what he samples or
the pace of his rhythms or the the
detail in his rhythms like the song
Manteca which has these really odd old
like old man vocals singing against
these very weird synthesizer leads or
the depressing chords and descending
bass guitar on the track Gilgamesh which
has these birds sampled throughout the
chorus too for a hip-hop beat it really
sounds like a funeral march and the
track poachers which has a strong desert
vibe to it the song tinseltown one of my
favorite tracks on here does have more
of an old-school blockhead vibe to it
and while I love the sad soulful horns
on the track 1,001 nights I wish this
song got developed a little bit more
into something with maybe a little bit
more structure because it feels like
this same horn sample is just being
repeated over and over I don't know
they're just some songs where I wish
they hit a little harder made a bit more
impact like the the potentially great
posse track on here fool's gold with
open mike eagle mocha only lucid and
billy woods on the track to the beat in
my opinion really sort of meanders and
when it does change the things that adds
to the equation are not really that
interesting like the very weak synth
melodies that that occur under the
second and fourth verses on this track
as far as Billy's rap style I'm not
really seeing a whole lot of change
between this LP and history will absolve
me he sounds just as passionate and
focused as he did last year maybe what
he's saying comes off a little more
coded but the more I listen to it the
more vivid this image becomes and the
more I feel like this is what Billy had
been doing with his life maybe up until
the point when he kind of started his
rap career
because he does throw in images of cops
extortion DA's busting through the wall
like the kool-aid guy paranoia dim
prospects girlfriends and old flames all
while throwing some moral undertones
under all of it like forgetting about
the golden rule for a few pieces of
silver I could be wrong about how
non-fictional this story is but Billy
doesn't really seem unafraid to toss in
a reference here and there to his
rapping or his rap career which he does
on the song hack he does on the song
Central Park where he reminisces a
little bit about helping kids out with
their fractions in measuring product out
but this is one of the few moments where
Billy goes into the technical and
descriptive side of selling drugs really
for the most part he's painting a
picture of this person's life while this
career move is kind of going on like on
the song poachers where he seems to be
getting involved with the family of
someone that he knows who got arrested
and taken away by the police for what I
assume is what Billy has been rapping
about there are a lot of great spots
like this on this LP my issue is that
toward the end I really sort of feel
like this picture this image this story
whatever you want to call it falls apart
a little bit and he doesn't consistently
deliver more imagery or just develop
more curves or more corners in this
shape that he's trying to create and I
don't necessarily feel like the features
on this album either add to the story
that door candy tells overall I did
enjoy this album a lot but I do feel
like Woods's portrait could have come in
clear the production could have been a
little bit more memorable at some points
but still I do feel like in a way door
candy is a more ambitious move for Billy
woods and if he continues to work with
the kind of storytelling that that
attempts to reach from the first track
of an album to the last track of an
album I could see an even greater
project coming from him in the future
I'm feeling a decent strong seven on
this thing if you've given it a listen
what did you think of it did you love it
did you hate it why what do you think I
should review next and that's it this
review is my opinion if you don't like
it here's a straw I want to give a shout
out to Egypt as well as feeding to
records all mistakes were intentional
only the strong subscribe
Billy woods the needle drop blockhead
forever
